---

<SiteLayout site="nookienook" title="Bra Size Calculator: Modern '+0' Method" description="Stop wearing the wrong size. Is your current bra actually giving you support, or are you just used to the discomfort?" canonical="https://nookienook.com/bra-size-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Modern Bra Size Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Calculate your true size using the modern '+0' measurement method for superior fit and support.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="underbustInput">Underbust Measurement (inches)</label>
        <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">Measured snugly directly under the breasts, parallel to the floor.</p>
        <input type="number" id="underbustInput" placeholder="e.g., 32" step="0.5" required />
      </div>

      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="bustInput">Bust Measurement (inches)</label>
        <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--text-secondary); margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">Measured loosely around the fullest part of the breasts.</p>
        <input type="number" id="bustInput" placeholder="e.g., 38" step="0.5" required />
      </div>

      <div class="error-message" id="errorMessage" style="display: none; color: #ef4444; margin-top: 1rem; font-weight: 500;"></div>

      <div class="result-card" id="resultCard" style="display: none;">
        <div class="result-label">Your Estimated US Size</div>
        <div class="result-value" id="resultValue">34D</div>
        <div class="sister-sizes" id="sisterSizes" style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); font-weight: 500;"></div>
        <div class="result-summary" style="margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.95rem;">
          This result uses the modern +0 sizing method. If you're used to adding 4 inches to your band size, this cup size may seem surprisingly large. Trust the math—a smaller band with larger cups provides vastly better support.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>The Methodology of Modern Bra Sizing</h2>
      <p>Finding a well-fitting bra is notoriously difficult, largely because the sizing standards established decades ago no longer reflect modern garment manufacturing or biomechanics. Industry estimates suggest that anywhere from 70% to 80% of women wear the wrong bra size. This calculator employs the modern "+0" (Plus Zero) method, moving away from outdated retail formulas that prioritize inventory management over physical support.</p>

      <h3>The Flaw in the "+4" Sizing Method</h3>
      <p>For decades, major lingerie retailers have instructed customers to measure their underbust and add 4 or 5 inches to calculate their band size. For example, an underbust of 30 inches would result in a 34-inch band. This is known as the "+4 method."</p>
      <p>This method was originally developed in the 1930s when bra bands were made from rigid, non-elastic fabrics. Adding inches was the only way a wearer could breathe or move. Modern bras, however, are made with highly elastic materials like spandex and elastane. When you add 4 inches to a modern, stretchy bra band, the resulting garment is entirely too loose. Because the band provides roughly 80% of a bra's structural support, a loose band forces the shoulder straps to carry the weight of the breasts, leading to back pain, shoulder indentations, and a band that constantly rides up the back.</p>

      <h3>The Superiority of the "+0" Method</h3>
      <p>This calculator relies strictly on the +0 method. Your band size should closely match your actual, physical underbust measurement.</p>

      <div style="background: var(--card-bg); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: 1.5rem 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 1.1rem;">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;"><strong>Step 1: The Band</strong></div>
        <div>Band Size = Snug Underbust (Rounded to nearest even number)</div>
        <div style="margin: 1rem 0 0.5rem;"><strong>Step 2: The Cup</strong></div>
        <div>Cup Size = Bust Measurement - Band Size</div>
        <div>(Where 1" difference = A, 2" = B, 3" = C, 4" = D, 5" = DD, etc.)</div>
      </div>

      <p>When you shift to the +0 method, two things happen mathematically: your band size decreases, and your cup size increases. This concept is often shocking to users. If you currently wear a 36B (calculated via the +4 method for a 32-inch underbust), the +0 method will likely place you in a 32DD or 32E. The volume of breast tissue held by the cups is nearly identical between a 36B and a 32DD; the difference is purely in how tightly the support structure wraps around the ribcage.</p>

      <h3>The Concept of Sister Sizes</h3>
      <p>In bra manufacturing, cup letters do not represent a static volume. A 'D' cup on a 32 band is significantly smaller than a 'D' cup on a 40 band. Cup volume is relative to the band size.</p>
      <p>When you need a different band size but want to keep the exact same volume in the cups, you look to <strong>Sister Sizes</strong>. The mathematical rule of sister sizing is simple: If you go up one band size, you must go down one cup letter. If you go down one band size, you must go up one cup letter.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>If your calculated size is a <strong>34D</strong>, but the band feels too tight in a specific brand, you would try a <strong>36C</strong>. The band is two inches larger, but the cups hold the same volume.</li>
        <li>If the 34 band feels too loose, you would try a <strong>32DD</strong>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Our calculator automatically generates your closest sister sizes so you can adjust your fit based on how specific brands scale their elasticity.</p>

      <h3>Variables Beyond Simple Mathematics</h3>
      <p>While calculating the exact mathematical difference is crucial (a concept also explored in our <a href="/percent-increase-calculator">percent increase calculator</a>), a bra is a three-dimensional structural garment. Two women with the exact same measurements may require different sizes or styles due to breast shape dynamics:</p>

      <h4>Breast Root and Projection</h4>
      <p>Breasts with a narrow "root" (where tissue attaches to the chest wall) that project outward heavily require deep, narrow cups. Breasts with a wide root that distribute volume across a larger area of the chest require wide, shallow cups. Two people requiring a 34F may find that one brand cuts their wire too narrow, while another cuts it too wide, despite the mathematical volume being identical.</p>

      <h4>Tissue Density</h4>
      <p>Dense, firm breast tissue will push back against a bra, requiring a highly structured cup to shape it. Softer, less dense tissue is more malleable and will conform to the shape of the bra. Those with softer tissue often find they need to size down slightly in the cup to prevent the top of the bra from wrinkling, even if their standing measurements suggest a larger size.</p>

      <p>Ultimately, a calculator is a highly accurate starting point. A properly fitting bra will feature a band that sits parallel to the floor without riding up, a center wire that tacks flat against the sternum, and cups that fully enclose the tissue without spillage or wrinkling. Trust the measurements, embrace the smaller band size, and prioritize structural support over outdated retail sizing dogmas.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the +0 or +4 method for bra sizing?</summary>
        <p>The +4 method is an outdated sizing technique where you add 4 or 5 inches to your underbust measurement to get your band size. The modern +0 method, which our calculator uses, sets your band size roughly equal to your actual snug underbust measurement in inches. This provides significantly better support, as the band should do 80% of the work.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I measure myself for a bra?</summary>
        <p>You need two measurements in inches. First, measure your underbust directly under your breasts, keeping the tape horizontal and comfortably snug. Second, measure your bust at the fullest part (usually over the nipples) without pulling the tape tight.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is my calculated cup size so much larger than what I normally wear?</summary>
        <p>This is very common when switching from the +4 method to the +0 method. Because the modern method gives you a smaller band size (closer to your actual underbust), the relative difference between your bust and underbust increases, resulting in a larger cup letter. However, the physical volume remains similar; a 34DD and a 38B actually hold roughly the same volume of breast tissue.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are sister sizes?</summary>
        <p>Sister sizes are bra sizes that hold the exact same volume in the cups, even though the band size and cup letter differ. If you go up a band size, you must go down a cup letter to maintain the same volume. For example, 34C, 36B, and 32D are all sister sizes. Our calculator provides these to help you fine-tune your fit.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How should a properly fitting bra feel?</summary>
        <p>The band should be snug and sit parallel to the floor, doing 80% of the supporting work without riding up your back. The center gore (the piece between the cups) should tack flat against your sternum. The cups should enclose the breast tissue completely without spilling over the top (quad-boob) or wrinkling. The straps should not dig into your shoulders or constantly slip off.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const underbustInput = document.getElementById('underbustInput');
      const bustInput = document.getElementById('bustInput');
      const resultCard = document.getElementById('resultCard');
      const resultValue = document.getElementById('resultValue');
      const sisterSizesDisplay = document.getElementById('sisterSizes');
      const errorMessage = document.getElementById('errorMessage');

      // US Cup sizing array (1 inch diff = A, 2 = B, etc.)
      const cupSizes = [
        'AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'DD', 'DDD/F', 'G', 'H', 'I', 'J', 'K', 'L', 'M', 'N', 'O'
      ];

      function calculateSize() {
        const underbustRaw = underbustInput.value;
        const bustRaw = bustInput.value;

        // Reset states
        resultCard.style.display = 'none';
        errorMessage.style.display = 'none';

        if (underbustRaw.trim() === '' || bustRaw.trim() === '') {
          return;
        }

        const underbust = parseFloat(underbustRaw);
        const bust = parseFloat(bustRaw);

        // Validation
        if (isNaN(underbust) || isNaN(bust) || underbust <= 0 || bust <= 0) {
          errorMessage.textContent = 'Please enter valid positive measurements.';
          errorMessage.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        if (bust < underbust) {
          errorMessage.textContent = 'Bust measurement cannot be smaller than underbust measurement.';
          errorMessage.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        if (underbust < 22 || underbust > 60) {
          errorMessage.textContent = 'Underbust measurement is outside typical calculation ranges (22" - 60").';
          errorMessage.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        // --- Core +0 Calculation Logic ---

        // 1. Calculate Band Size
        // Round to nearest even number
        let bandSize = Math.round(underbust);
        if (bandSize % 2 !== 0) {
          // If odd, generally sizing up to the next even number is standard for comfort
          // However, rounding to nearest even is more precise mathematically.
          // e.g. 29.4 -> 29 -> 30.  28.6 -> 29 -> 30.
          bandSize += 1;
        }

        // 2. Calculate Cup Size Difference
        // Difference is bust - bandSize
        let difference = bust - bandSize;

        // Cup indexes: 0 diff = AA, 1 diff = A, 2 = B, etc.
        // We round the difference to the nearest whole inch
        let cupIndex = Math.round(difference);

        // Edge case handling for very small differences
        if (cupIndex < 0) cupIndex = 0;

        // Check if cup size exceeds our array
        if (cupIndex >= cupSizes.length) {
          errorMessage.textContent = 'Size exceeds standard US sizing chart capabilities. We recommend consulting a specialized fitter.';
          errorMessage.style.display = 'block';
          return;
        }

        const cupLetter = cupSizes[cupIndex];
        const primarySize = `${bandSize}${cupLetter}`;

        // 3. Calculate Sister Sizes
        // Sister size down: Band - 2, Cup Index + 1
        // Sister size up: Band + 2, Cup Index - 1
        let sisterDown = '';
        let sisterUp = '';

        if (cupIndex + 1 < cupSizes.length && bandSize - 2 >= 22) {
          sisterDown = `${bandSize - 2}${cupSizes[cupIndex + 1]}`;
        }

        if (cupIndex - 1 >= 0) {
          sisterUp = `${bandSize + 2}${cupSizes[cupIndex - 1]}`;
        }

        // Format sister sizes string
        let sisterTextArray = [];
        if (sisterDown) sisterTextArray.push(`Snugger Band: ${sisterDown}`);
        if (sisterUp) sisterTextArray.push(`Looser Band: ${sisterUp}`);

        let sisterText = '';
        if (sisterTextArray.length > 0) {
          sisterText = 'Sister Sizes: ' + sisterTextArray.join(' | ');
        } else {
          sisterText = 'No standard sister sizes available for these measurements.';
        }

        // Display results
        resultValue.textContent = primarySize;
        sisterSizesDisplay.textContent = sisterText;
        resultCard.style.display = 'block';
      }

      // Add event listeners for real-time calculation
      underbustInput.addEventListener('input', calculateSize);
      bustInput.addEventListener('input', calculateSize);
    });
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
